ROOT CAUSE: `cJSON.c:798` dereferences `input_end` in `while (*input_end != '\"')` without first checking that `input_end` is still inside `input_buffer`. In the failing run, `input_buffer->content` points to the five-byte buffer `"abc\0`, `input_buffer->length` is `5`, and `input_end` starts at `content + 1`; because there is no closing quote, the loop advances over `a`, `b`, `c`, and the terminating NUL at index 4, then increments to `content + 5`. The next loop-condition evaluation reads `*input_end` at offset 5, which is one past the valid buffer range `[0, 4]`, so AddressSanitizer reports a heap-buffer-overflow and aborts before the later “string ended unexpectedly” check can run.

LOCAL FIX: Restore a bounds check in the scan loop so the code never dereferences `input_end` after it reaches `input_buffer->length`; the existing post-loop check will then fail cleanly for unterminated strings. Minimal edit: ```diff
--- a/cJSON.c
+++ b/cJSON.c
@@ -795,7 +795,8 @@ static cJSON_bool parse_string(cJSON * const item, parse_buffer * const input_bu
         /* calculate approximate size of the output (overestimate) */
         size_t allocation_length = 0;
         size_t skipped_bytes = 0;
-        while (*input_end != '\"')
+        while (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) < input_buffer->length) &&
+               (*input_end != '\"'))
         {
             /* is escape sequence */
             if (input_end[0] == '\\')
``` With this change, the failing input advances `input_end` to offset 5, the loop exits without reading offset 5, and the following `if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length) || (*input_end != '\"'))` takes the failure path safely.

GLOBAL FIX: Replace raw pointer-scanning loops over `parse_buffer` with a bounded cursor API/invariant that combines pointer movement and access checks, e.g. helper functions like `parse_peek(buffer, relative_index, &ch)` and `parse_advance(buffer, n)` that refuse reads beyond `length`; then string parsing, number parsing, and escape handling cannot accidentally dereference first and validate later. A structural fix would also make `parse_buffer` expose an explicit `end` pointer or remaining-length view and require all parsers to consume through that bounded view rather than doing ad hoc `content + offset` pointer arithmetic.

